   <title type="text">Online Exhibition: TEXTS FROM ANCIENT EGYPT. Highlights from the Collection of the Leiden Papyrological Institute </title>
   <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-a.html">TEXTS FROM ANCIENT EGYPT. Highlights from the Collection of the Leiden Papyrological Institute</a><b>&nbsp;</b><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><b><img alt="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT100207&amp;thumbed=4" class="decoded" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT100207&amp;thumbed=4" /> </b></span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;">Online exhibition on the occasion of the 80th anniversary of the foundation ‘Het Leids Papyrologisch Instituut’. </span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-b.html">Not just Greek</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-b.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT146995&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Most texts from  the collection of the Leiden Papyrological Institute are in Greek, but  some are written in Egyptian (Hieratic, Demotic, Coptic) and in Latin.  Take a look at examples of non-Greek writing.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-b.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-c.html">Of course people paid taxes</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-c.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147003&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Ostraca (mostly  pottery, but also limestone shards) formed a cheap alternative for  papyrus. Pots were found in every household. Pots also break easily. The  shards were then recycled as writing material. Tax receipts are  generally written on ostraca.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-c.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-d.html">Always borrowing things</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-d.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147004&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Written proof of a  loan has always been important. Take a look at examples of loans of  grain, wine,&nbsp;and money, and a&nbsp;loan on mortgage.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-d.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-e.html">Other official records</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-e.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147025&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Many papyrus  documents are official. Examples of a registration of birth, an  arrangement for&nbsp;overdue instalments and&nbsp;a&nbsp;receipt for payment in money  and kind.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-e.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-f.html">Private letters</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-f.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147028&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">The meaning of  many letters escapes us, when the context is lacking, as is the case in  these two private letters on papyrus, from the third and sixth centuries  AD.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-f.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibtion-g.html">A mummy with a name</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibtion-g.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147005&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Egypt largely  consisted of desert. Wood was a relatively rare and expensive commodity.  Wooden mummy labels were often shaped like tomb stones and hung around  the neck of a mummy with rope. They mostly mention the name and age of  the mummy.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibtion-g.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-h.html">Reading Homer in the Roman period</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-h.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT146976&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">In antiquity  people loved to read the authors we now call classic. Texts were copied  on demand. The handwriting of literary papyri is neater and more regular  than documentary writing. Some of our literary texts on papyrus: Homer,  Hesiod, Plato, Euripides and a fable.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-h.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-i.html">Wax tablets</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-i.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT147007&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">Wax tablets are  little planks hollowed out on two sides, and then filled with wax. A  pointed  stilus  was used to write letters in the wax surface. The flat  back end of the  stilus  was then applied to erase the text, rendering  wax tablets the ideal notebook for children at school.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-i.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">      </span><article class="section-article">                   <h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-j.html">Small history versus big history</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-j.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT146985&amp;thumbed=4" /></a></span>                                                    <span style="font-size: x-small;">All papyri, each  in their own way, provide information on aspects of life in antiquity.  For example the complaint of a private individual about the theft of  dresses, and another text on a visit of Emperor Hadrian.</span><br />                                 <div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-j.html">Read more</a></span></div><span style="font-size: x-small;"><br class="clear" /></span>  </article><span style="font-size: x-small;">                          </span><h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-k.html">Magic, religion, superstition</a></span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;">                                <a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-k.html"><img class="grid-2 alpha" src="http://beeldbank.leidenuniv.nl/ImageDisplay.php?uid=FT146986&amp;thumbed=4" /></a>                                                    </span><span style="font-size: x-small;">Magic, religion  and superstition were closely related in Antiquity. In this section we  combined a drawing of a temple, a&nbsp;list of gods, magic, horoscopes,  amulets and&nbsp;Christian texts.</span><br /><span style="font-size: x-small;">                                </span><div class="read-more"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a href="http://www.hum.leiden.edu/papyrological-institute/papyrus-collection/exhibition-k.html">Read more</a></span></div></blockquote><br /><br />]]></content>
